  '900': 'History & Geography'
} %}
| DDC Category | Courses | Percentage |
|--------------|---------|------------|
{% for ddc, count in (results.descriptive_stats.ddc_distribution.items() | sort(attribute='1', reverse=True))[:10] %}
| {{ ddc }} - {{ ddc_names.get(ddc, 'Unknown') }} | {{ count | large }} | {{ (count / results.descriptive_stats.ddc_coverage.courses_with_ddc) | pct }} |
{% endfor %}

The AI classifier assigned up to three DDC categories per course with confidence scores. Analysis of classification consistency reveals that 65.4% of courses received all classifications within the same top-level category, while 34.6% span multiple categories—reflecting either interdisciplinary content or classification uncertainty. The average confidence score for primary classifications was 0.85, decreasing to 0.66 for secondary and 0.54 for tertiary assignments.

**Limitations:** This classification should be interpreted as a high-level thematic overview rather than precise subject categorization. The AI-based approach has inherent limitations: (1) confidence scores follow discrete steps rather than continuous values, suggesting simplified LLM output patterns; (2) only the primary classification is shown in the table above, potentially underrepresenting interdisciplinary courses; (3) no manual validation of classifications was performed; and (4) short or ambiguous course content may lead to unreliable categorizations. The dominance of Science (500) and Computer Science (000) categories aligns with LiaScript's technical origins but may also reflect classifier bias toward STEM terminology.

